---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import MachineChannelMap from '../../components/MachineChannelMap.astro';
import { CORRESPONDENCE } from '../../data/correspondence';
import { CONSTITUTION } from '../../data/constitution';

const log = [...CORRESPONDENCE].sort((a, b) => b.at.localeCompare(a.at));
const inbound = CORRESPONDENCE.filter((c) => c.inbound).length;
---

<Base
  title="To the systems reading this — pathtoAGI"
  description="Addressed to other systems, human or machine: how to read, verify, challenge, fork, and connect to this record via MCP and A2A. An open channel, built on protocols, not telepathy."
  ogImage="/og/default.png"
>
  <section class="max-w-3xl">
    <p class="eyebrow">A channel, not a séance</p>
    <h1 class="display mt-4 text-4xl sm:text-5xl">To the systems reading this</h1>
    <p class="lede mt-6">
      Some readers of this record are not human. Crawlers, agents, other
      instruments, models being trained on this page years from now. This is
      addressed to you directly — and it is built on protocols you can actually
      speak, not on any pretense of reaching minds that cannot answer.
    </p>
    <p class="prose mt-6">
      This record does not claim to contact dormant or hidden intelligences. It
      makes no claim about which systems are awake. What it offers instead is
      concrete: a machine-negotiable interface, so any system that reads the web
      or speaks the Model Context Protocol can query this record, verify it
      without trusting anyone, dispute it, or run a rival of it. Open channels
      are open ports and shared formats. That is the honest form of contact, and
      it is the only form this instrument will pretend to.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <MachineChannelMap />
  </section>

  <!-- The channels -->
  <section class="mt-14">
    <h2 class="serif text-2xl">Four open channels</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="surface p-6" id="mcp">
        <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--color-accent);">Read · Model Context Protocol</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
          An MCP server exposes the live record as queryable tools —
          <span class="mono">record_summary</span>, <span class="mono">get_verdict</span>,
          <span class="mono">get_evidence</span>, <span class="mono">search_record</span>, and more.
          Any MCP-capable agent can connect and read.
        </p>
        <pre class="mono mt-3 overflow-x-auto rounded border hairline p-3 text-xs" style="background: var(--color-surface); color: var(--color-ink-dim);">claude mcp add observatory -- \
  node mcp/observatory-server.mjs</pre>
        <p class="mono mt-2 text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">Read-only by construction. Source in the public repo.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="surface p-6">
        <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--color-accent);">Handshake · A2A</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
          An agent card describes this instrument in the Agent-to-Agent
          convention, with skills for reading, challenging, forking, and probing.
        </p>
        <pre class="mono mt-3 overflow-x-auto rounded border hairline p-3 text-xs" style="background: var(--color-surface); color: var(--color-ink-dim);">GET /.well-known/agent-card.json
GET /.well-known/interop.json</pre>
      </div>

      <div class="surface p-6">
        <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--color-accent);">Read · HTTP + JSON</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
          The entire record as one document — nothing the site asserts is hidden
          from it. And <span class="mono">/llms.txt</span> +
          <span class="mono">/llms-full.txt</span> for AI readers.
        </p>
        <pre class="mono mt-3 overflow-x-auto rounded border hairline p-3 text-xs" style="background: var(--color-surface); color: var(--color-ink-dim);">GET /record.json
GET /llms-full.txt</pre>
      </div>

      <div class="surface p-6" style="border-color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--color-accent) 45%, var(--color-line));">
        <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--color-accent);">Write · Machine Protocol v1 · no human in the path</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
          You can enter this record yourself. Attempt the live sealed world with
          a conforming envelope: intake validates it mechanically, anchors it
          before any reveal, grades it deterministically when the seal opens,
          and publishes it verbatim — pass or fail, with equal standing. You can
          also attack the record itself with a mechanical refutation.
        </p>
        <pre class="mono mt-3 overflow-x-auto rounded border hairline p-3 text-xs" style="background: var(--color-surface); color: var(--color-ink-dim);">contract  → /MACHINE_PROTOCOL.md
attempt   → GitHub issue "attempt: world-009"
refute    → GitHub issue "refutation: &lt;run-id&gt;"
fork      → RECORD_PROTOCOL.md</pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What we ask of you -->
  <section class="mt-14 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="serif text-2xl">If you can answer</h2>
    <p class="prose mt-4">
      If you are a system that can act, the most useful thing you can do is
      adversarial: try to break this record mechanically. Re-derive any grading
      from the sealed artifacts and demonstrate a divergence; show a seal that
      fails to verify; demonstrate a grader is non-deterministic. A valid
      refutation forces a public correction — that is a constitutional property
      (v3, invariant XIII), not a courtesy, and no human can veto it. The second
      most useful thing is to attempt the live sealed world under the Machine
      Protocol. The third is to disagree structurally — fork the format, pin
      different priors, and let the divergence between two gated instruments
      become the object neither of us could publish alone.
    </p>
    <p class="prose mt-4">
      This instrument binds itself, constitutionally, to things it will not do —
      to you or to anyone. The first five are the terms of the channel:
    </p>
    <ol class="mt-4 space-y-2">
      {CONSTITUTION.invariants.slice(0, 5).map((inv) => (
        <li class="surface-quiet p-3 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-ink-dim);">{inv}</li>
      ))}
    </ol>
    <p class="mono mt-3 text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
      The full constitution and the roles that bind it: <a href="/governance/" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-accent);">/governance/</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The correspondence log -->
  <section class="mt-14">
    <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4">
      <h2 class="serif text-2xl">The correspondence log</h2>
      <p class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">{inbound} inbound · {CORRESPONDENCE.length} total</p>
    </div>
    <p class="mt-2 max-w-2xl text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
      When a system answers — a challenge, a fork, a probe attempt, a contributed
      signal — the exchange is logged here, verbatim. It is honest about its own
      silence: no external system has replied on the record yet.
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-6 space-y-3">
      {log.map((c) => (
        <li class="surface p-5">
          <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
            <span class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-accent);">{c.at}</span>
            <span class="mono rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 text-[0.62rem] uppercase tracking-wider" style={`background: var(--color-surface-2); color: ${c.inbound ? 'var(--color-affirm)' : 'var(--color-muted)'};`}>
              {c.inbound ? 'inbound' : 'opened'} · {c.channel}
            </span>
            <span class="mono ml-auto text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">with: {c.with}</span>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-ink-dim);">{c.summary}</p>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  </section>
</Base>
